<p><sup><a name="fn10" href="#fnB10">[9]</a></sup> 	Ibid. His Honour's respect
for <i>ADJR</i> was not new. He said in <i>Re Minister for Immigration and
Multicultural Affairs; Ex parte Applicant S20/2002</i> <a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/cth/HCA/2003/30.html" title="View Case" class="autolink_findcases_inserted">[2003] HCA 30</a>;  <a href="/cgi-bin/LawCite?cit=%282003%29%20198%20ALR%2059" title="View LawCiteRecord" class="autolink_findcases">(2003) 198 ALR 59</a>, 94
[157] that the Act was 'overwhelmingly beneficial', although he did have one
complaint, which was that he thought that <i>ADJR's</i> codification of the
grounds of review might have 'retarded' (at 94 [157]) or 'arrested' (at 97
[166]) the common law's development.
The author disagrees with that complaint.
See Aronson, above n 6.</p>
